We need to perform some preprocessing steps before applying KMeans.

  • Handling Missing Values
  • Encoding Categorical Features
  • Normalizing features
  • Reducing Dimensionality
  • Handling Noise and Outlier

Preprocessing¶

First, let's see how many features we have and what their types are. We have 27 columns, one of which is ID. Most of the features are categorical.

Missing Values¶

KMeans cannot handle missing values, so we consider removing or replacing them.

If features have an approximately normal distribution, we replace Nan with the average of the column. Otherwise, we use the median. For the remaining categorical columns, we replace Nan values with mode. If the number of missing values is small enough, we delete the corresponding rows.

In [ ]:
ins_df['OCCUPATION'].fillna(ins_df['OCCUPATION'].mode()[0], inplace = True)
ins_df.dropna(subset = ['AGE'], inplace = True)
ins_df['YOJ'].fillna(ins_df['YOJ'].median(), inplace = True)
ins_df['INCOME'].fillna(ins_df['INCOME'].median(), inplace = True)
ins_df['HOME_VAL'].fillna(ins_df['HOME_VAL'].median(), inplace = True)
ins_df['CAR_AGE'].fillna(ins_df['CAR_AGE'].median(), inplace = True)

Convert Categorical to Numeric¶

Since KMeans only works with numeric features, we need to encode categorical columns into numerical. The occupation column is first divided into blue-collar and white-collar jobs based on the data description, and each one is assigned a numerical value.

mask = (ins_df['OCCUPATION'] == 'z_Blue Collar')
ins_df.loc[mask, 'OCCUPATION'] = 1
ins_df.loc[-mask,'OCCUPATION'] = 0

Normalization¶

Since KMeans uses Euclidean distance to measure similarity between points, features with larger values will have a larger impact. We apply data scaling and normalization to avoid this. We use MinMaxScaler (min = 0, max = 1), which doesn't assume that the shape of all features follows a normal distribution. Also, better results have been achieved compared to StandardScaler.

scaler = MinMaxScaler()
scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(num_df))

Outliers¶

Outliers may distract the centers of clusters and affect KMeans performance. To mitigate this effect, we used zscore with threshold 3 and considered points outside this threshold to be outliers and removed them.

In [ ]:
import scipy.stats as stats
z = np.abs(stats.zscore(scaled_df))
threshold = 3
new_ins_df = scaled_df[(z < threshold).all(axis=1)]
new_ins_df

Dimensionality Reduction¶

KMeans cannot scale up to high-dimensional data because the distance between any two data objects in a high-dimensional space is the same. We try dimensionality reduction techniques like PCA to address this issue. We tried running KMeans with different numbers of components. The best result happened when we had two components.

In [ ]:
pca = PCA()
pca.fit(new_ins_df)
cumsum = np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
plt.plot(cumsum)
Out[ ]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x1d81e83c3d0>]
In [ ]:
def dim_red(scaled_df,n):
    if n > 1 :
        pca = PCA(n_components = n)
        data_pca = pca.fit_transform(scaled_df)
        return pd.DataFrame(data_pca)
    return scaled_df

Silhouette¶

from yellowbrick.cluster import SilhouetteVisualizer
In [ ]:
def plot_scores(k_values,scores,inertia):
    plt.figure(figsize = (20,10))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    plt.plot(k_values, scores, marker = 'o')
    plt.xlabel("K")
    plt.ylabel("silhouette score")
    plt.title("Silhouette Score")

    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    plt.plot(k_values, inertia, marker = 'o')
    plt.xlabel("K")
    plt.ylabel("Inertia")
    plt.title("Inertia")
In [ ]:
k_values = [k for k in range(2,10)]

def search_kmeans(X, k_values):
    scores = []
    inertia = []
    for k in k_values:
        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
        y_pred = kmeans.fit_predict(X)
        labels = kmeans.labels_
        sc = silhouette_score(X, labels)
        scores.append(sc)
        inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)
        visualizer = SilhouetteVisualizer(kmeans, colors='yellowbrick', is_fitted=True)
        visualizer.fit(X)      
        visualizer.show()        
        
    plot_scores(k_values,scores,inertia)
    return scores, inertia

Finally, we executed KMeans with k ranging from 2 to 9 and displayed the silhouette coefficient for each sample per cluster to assess the density and distance between clusters. Clusters with higher scores have wider silhouettes, but clusters that are less cohesive will fall short of the average score across all clusters. We selected k = 9 based on this and the average score. Each color represent a distinct cluster.

We don't need to normalize longitude and latitude as we use haversine as a distance metric in DBSCAN. Haversine is used to determine the distance in kilometers between coordinate pairs. We give epsilon in kilometers and we should convert it into radians when applying haversine distance.

In [ ]:
def draw_sc(X,min_points,epsilon):

    scores = []
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,12))
    nrwos = len(min_points) // 4 + 1
    for p in range(len(min_points)):
        s = []
        for e in epsilon:
            dbscan = DBSCAN(eps= e/kms_per_radian, min_samples= min_points[p], algorithm = 'ball_tree', metric='haversine')
            dbscan.fit(X)
            labels = dbscan.labels_
            num_clusters = len(set(labels))
            if num_clusters > 1:
                sc = round(silhouette_score(X, labels),4)
            else:
                sc = 0
            s.append([min_points[p],e,sc,set(labels)])
            scores.append([min_points[p],e,sc,set(labels)])
            
        temp = np.array(s)
        plt.subplot(nrwos,4,p + 1)
        plt.plot(temp[:,1],temp[:,2])
        plt.title(f"min points = {min_points[p]}")
        plt.xlabel("epsilon")
        plt.ylabel("silhouette score")
    return pd.DataFrame(scores,columns=['min_points','epsilon','silhouette_score','clusters'])

First we executed DBSCAN with min_points ranging from 15 to 25 and epsilon ranging from 80 to 200 km. for each value chosen for min point we plotted average silhouette score. As we can see, the best score achieved when epsilon was approximately 170 km and min_points was around 20.

Epsilon Values¶

  • If the epsilon is too large, the clusters will merge and no points considered to be noise(noises will become core points or border points).(right plot)
  • If the epsilon is too small, if any cluster will form it would be small and many points will be considered noise.(left plot)

Min_points Values¶

  • A very large value of min_points will result in many points being labeled as noise or very few dense clusters being formed.(right plot)

  • A very small value of min_points will result in many small clusters being formed(noises will form small clusters) or clusters being merged together.(left plot)

From the scatter plot, we can see that there are clusters with different densities, and since the minpts and epsilon are the same for all clusters in DBSCAN, we think it's the reason why DBSCAN didn't work very well.

New Feature¶

Looking at the attributes, the only attribute connected to the geographic location is 'place' which is a textual description of the location near to the earthquake. The 'place' attribute is made up of the names of the cities and countries where earthquakes happened. We can use Gower distance when we have mixed data (precompute the distance matrix in DBSCAN) or encode categorical data and use Euclidean distance. But, we decided not to add this feature.
